Goals for Glory: What Does It Take To Score (and Assist) as a Pro?¶

Table of Contents¶

  • Introduction

  • Exploratory Data Analysis
  • Conclusions

Introduction¶

This analysis looks at data for professional football/soccer players and matches across a variety of pro leagues. We will take a brief look at the best strikers and passers and see factors/attributes effects their ratings or performance. For strikers, we will look at the effects age has on their overall ratings as a player and their potential. For the passers, we will focus our analysis on the players who make the crucial last pass (a.k.a assist) to the eventual goal scorer and their strongest attributes.

The database (and schema, metadata, etc.) used in this analsysis can been found on kaggle here.

The database.sqlite file used for this analysis can be found here. Download should start automatically

You will need to download the database to be able to run this notebook. Be sure to save the database.sqlite file in the same folder as this notebook or your project (or specify it's location in your use).

WOAH, that is a lot of attributes for each individual player! The Player_Attributes table lists all of the attributes identified in the video game FIFA (by EA sports) for each player. We also see common player IDs as was found in the Players table, great!

Taking a closer look, we can also see that there are multiple entires for individual players in the table. For example, player_api_id = 505942 alone has 4 entries.

What's going on here???

Judging by the date column, it looks as though player attributes are updated as time goes on. This could be useful if we wanted to get an idea of player "evolultion" (i.e. player improvement) over time, but we will leave this for another analysis. For now, I am only interested in the most up-to-date attributes and rating for each player.

Joining Tables from Database¶

It would be useful to have all of the player data in one Pandas Dataframe for ease of use in our analysis. Let's join the Player and Player_Attributes tables in our SQL query to acheive this.

We will also address the multiple entries for each player_api_id that occur in the Player_Attributes table in the query, only using the latest entry in the database for any player in this analysis.

In [7]:
# The backslashes, \ , in the query below are used to keep the string continuing onto the next line
# for easier reading of the  query structure. They have no purpose in the query itself!

# NOTE: 
# You cannot have spaces after the "\" on each line of the query. If you do, it will "break" the string, and the query will not run!
# MAX(pa.date) ensures we only query the latest values by date for each player (ingore older player attributes)

query = "WITH t1 AS (SELECT pa.player_api_id player_api_id_attr, pa.overall_rating, pa.potential, MAX(pa.date) rating_date,\
                        pa.preferred_foot, pa.attacking_work_rate, pa.defensive_work_rate,\
                        pa.crossing, pa.finishing, pa.heading_accuracy, short_passing, pa.volleys,\
                        pa.dribbling, pa.curve, pa.free_kick_accuracy, pa.long_passing, pa.ball_control,\
                        pa.acceleration, pa.sprint_speed, pa.agility, pa.reactions, pa.balance, pa.shot_power,\
                        pa.jumping, pa.stamina, pa.strength, pa.long_shots, pa.aggression, pa.interceptions,\
                        pa.positioning, pa.vision, pa.penalties, pa.marking, pa.standing_tackle, pa.sliding_tackle\
                        FROM Player_Attributes pa\
                        GROUP BY 1\
                        ORDER BY 1)\
        SELECT p.*, t1.*\
        FROM Player p\
        JOIN t1\
        ON p.player_api_id = t1.player_api_id_attr"

player = pd.read_sql(query, conn)

It looks like the attacking/defensive_work_rate columns have some error values mixed amongst the standard inputs of low, medium, high. Let's set these error values to NaN and change the string inputs to numeric values, where:

low = 1
medium = 2
high = 3

In [9]:
### ATTACKING_WORK_RATE
# assign low, medium, high numeric values
player.attacking_work_rate.replace(to_replace='low', value=1, inplace=True)
player.attacking_work_rate.replace(to_replace='medium', value=2, inplace=True)
player.attacking_work_rate.replace(to_replace='high', value=3, inplace=True)

# set to numeric values, set non-numeric like string to NaN
player['attacking_work_rate'] = pd.to_numeric(player.attacking_work_rate, errors = 'coerce')
player.attacking_work_rate.mask(player.attacking_work_rate > 3, np.NaN, inplace=True)    # set any values outside valid range (1-3) as NaN
player.attacking_work_rate.mask(player.attacking_work_rate < 0, np.NaN, inplace=True)    # set any values outside valid range (1-3) as NaN

### DEFENSIVE_WORK_RATE
# assign low, medium, high numeric values
player.defensive_work_rate.replace(to_replace='low', value=1, inplace=True)
player.defensive_work_rate.replace(to_replace='medium', value=2, inplace=True)
player.defensive_work_rate.replace(to_replace='high', value=3, inplace=True)

# set to numeric values, set non-numeric like string to NaN
player['defensive_work_rate'] = pd.to_numeric(player.defensive_work_rate, errors = 'coerce')
player.defensive_work_rate.mask(player.defensive_work_rate > 3.0, np.NaN, inplace=True)    # set any values outside valid range (1-3) as NaN
player.defensive_work_rate.mask(player.defensive_work_rate < 0, np.NaN, inplace=True)    # set any values outside valid range (1-3) as NaN

This looks pretty good, we have fixed the birthday column to a datetime, and I don't see any issues in the descriptive statistic summry for each column, but we don't have any performance stats for any of the players! We are specifically interested in goals and assists.

Based on the metadata for the dataset on kaggle, the goal and assist data is stored in the Match table, in the column goal. Let's take a look at this next to see what we find.

Get Match & Goal Data¶

Let's start by querying the Match table to see what data is available.

NOTE:

  1. I have removed rows from the table where there is no goal data (14,217 rows total). This leaves 11,762 rows of where goal data is available. The reason for this missing goal data in the origianl SQLite database is unknown.
  2. NULL values were NOT replaced with any other value (e.g., replaced with mean) due to the sheer number of rows with missing data for goals (> 50% of total rows). Any cleaning of the missing data would could skew the distribution of data or could misrepresent any individual player's stats which I do not believe is appropriate in this analysis.

I am aware that this missing goal data may be in a sense discrediting goals/assits for players where they actually scored or assisted but no match goal data was recorded. However, due to the number rows missing goal data, I think any cleaning or replacement of missing values would do more harm than good to the analysis.

Hmmm... looks like the goal data is stored in an XML string. This will require some parsing/cleaning to get useable data, which we will work thourgh below.

Making sense of the goal column XML strings¶

After some investigation, and looking through the associated forums on kaggle for this dataset, I found:

Knut Behrends wrote (see link) :

"With regard to the XML fragment, I think 'player1' element means this guy scored, 'player2' made the assist. I've looked it up for this game, Manchester United vs Newcastle, first game in Season 2008/2009, the player IDs are correct."

Much thanks to Knut Behrends for his efforts to confirm the meanings of "player1" and "player2" in the XML strings. I will assume his findings are correct for all matches included in this analysis.

Cleaning up the goal data¶

For each goal scored in a match, the XML string lists the scoring player (player1) and the assist (player2). So we need to read through each string of XML for every match, and append each goal scored and each assist to a list of goal scorers and assisting players (or somtheing similar).

In order to parse the XML to pull out the relevant player1 and player2 occurences (as described by Knut Behrends), we will need to use Python's built in XML package (see docs). A good tutorial on using XML, by Charles Severance at the University of Michigan, can be found here. This really helped me understand how to use the XML package.

Step 1: Parsing XML Data¶

We will need some helper functions to parse the XML data in each cell. Let's lay them out below:

In [16]:
# define helper functions
def find_goal_players(xml_string):
    '''This function parses XML string from each match
    and returns a list of players who scored a goal
    for that match
    '''
    tree = ET.fromstring(xml_string)        # create XML tree
    scorers = tree.findall('.//player1')    # find all player1 elements in tree 
    
    # loop through player1 elements and store their value (the player id) in a list
    scorers_players_list = [player.text for player in scorers] 

    return scorers_players_list


def find_assist_players(xml_string):
    '''This function parses XML string from each match
    and returns a list of players who had an assist
    for that match
    '''
    tree = ET.fromstring(xml_string)        # create XML tree
    assists = tree.findall('.//player2')    # find all player2 elements in tree 

    # loop through player2 elements and store their value (the player id) in a list
    assists_players_list = [player.text for player in assists]

    return assists_players_list
Step 2: Get list of all goal scorers and assists for all matches.¶

Let's use these helper functions to get a list of the player_api_id's for each goal and assist made in all of the matches

In [17]:
# get panda series of just goal XML strings (for ease of reading code)
xml_goals = match.goal

# create empty lists for goal scoreres and assists
players_who_scored = []
players_who_assist = []

# loop through all of the matches
for index, value in xml_goals.iteritems():
    
    xml_string = value   # read in XML string
    
    scored_temp = find_goal_players(xml_string)   # get list of players who scored for each match
    assist_temp = find_assist_players(xml_string)    # get list of players with assists for each match
    
    players_who_scored.append(scored_temp)    # append lists of scoring players from match (this creates a list of lists)
    players_who_assist.append(assist_temp)    # append lists of assist player from match (this creates a list of lists)
    
players_who_scored = [scorer for sub_list in players_who_scored for scorer in sub_list]    # flatten list of lists
players_who_assist = [assist for sub_list in players_who_assist for assist in sub_list]    # flatten list of lists

print("Players who scored: ", players_who_scored[:10])  # show first ten values of list as check
print("Players who assist: ", players_who_assist[:10])  # show first ten values of list as check

Step 3: Count # of goals/assits for each player¶

We use the occurences of each player_api_id since the XML strings log the player WHO scored or assisted for a given goal, not how many goals or assists that player had in any given game.

Once we have a count of the number of goals and/or assists each player had (if any), we will need to assign them to the player_name's in our Player pandas dataframe.

In [22]:
for index, value in player.player_api_id.iteritems():    # loop though series of player_api_id's
    
    player.at[index,'goals'] = player_goal_counts.get(str(value),0)        # look up # of goals for each player_api_id,
                                                                           # assign to new "goals" column
    player.at[index,'assists'] = player_assist_counts.get(str(value),0)    # look up # of goals for each player_api_id,
                                                                           # assign to new "assists" column

Great, now we have two datasets for the top scorers and passers. Let's move onto some EDA.

Exploratory Data Analysis¶

Let's first take a quick look at how all of the data columns correlate with one another for both top scorers (strikers) and top passers (quantified by assists made).

It looks like there is a variety attributes that are positively correlated with number of goals a player scores, as well as some attributes that are neagtively correlated with goals scored.

At first glance, finishing, volleys, ball_control, recations, shot_power, positioning, and penalties appear to be the most strongly correlated with the number of goals a player scores.

We will be focusing on how a striker's age affects their overall_rating and potential. At first glance of the heatmap above, it is seems that age is negatively correlated with both overall_rating and potential. But to what degree? Are we confident that age is a good predictor of overall_rating or potential? Let's explore this more below.

Research Question 1: How Does Age Affect Strikers?¶

One might expect that a striker will mature with age leading to a rise in overall rating as they gain experience, but do players start to recede in skill at a certain age? Similarly, how does player potential change as strikers age? One might guess that potential decreases with age.

Hypothesis 1: Overall_rating varies linearly with age, as a player gets older, they improve.

Hypothesis 2: Player potential reduces with age.

Age vs. Overall Rating¶

We will start using a hexbin plot as it gives us a good idea of how the distributions of age and overall_rating overlap with one another (both range and density). A scatter plot might be a tempting first attempt of gaining some insight, but a scatter makes it hard to know how many players exist a specific age & overall_rating pairing.

Note:
The formatting lines to get the colorbar for the density of points to display correctly were found here. Some minor modifications were made to account for compatitbilty with this code.

In [100]:
# calculate R^2 value based on R, for print below
r_squared = stats.pearsonr(strikers['age'], strikers['overall_rating'])[0] ** 2

print("R-squared =", r_squared)                

R-squared = 0.0872278247402

Based on a linear regression of the data, it is actually expected that the overall_rating for a striker would decrease with age. However, the linear regression poorly fits the data with a coefficient of determination (R-squared) of 0.09. This means that only 9% of the variance in overall_rating is predicted by a player's age. It is likely that other factors are influencing a strikers overall rating, and cannot be well explained by age alone. Based on this information it is reasonable to reject Hypothesis 1.

From a more qualitative veiwpoint, most strikers with an overall rating of 85 or higher are found in the age range of 25 to 35 years old. This suggests that for the best strikers in the pro leagues, there is a prime age for top performers, though this dynamic is not well captured by a linear relationship.

Age vs Player Potential¶

Let's take a look at how player potential varies with age for strikers. Let's start off with another hexbin plot as it captures both the spread and the density of value pairs for age and potential.

As expected, a player's potential generally decreases as their age increases. This trend is shown by the best fit line. The denser (darker) regions of the hexpbin plot also exhibit a general trend of decreasing potential with age (with some variation of course).

As with the age vs overall_rating, the linear relationship is not extremely strong across the entire dataset of strikers (though considerably stronge than age vs overall_rating), with a coefficient fo determination of 0.27. In other words, 27% of the variation in a player's potential is predicted by a player's age. Similar to overall_rating, there are likely other factors in addition to age that are affecting player potential.

What about the difference in overall_rating and potential, or what we could call remaining_potential, as players get older. At this stage in our analysis it seems that this might be what our question was really getting at... does the difference between overall_rating and potential trend towards zero as a player gets older?

Perhaps we should revise Hypthesis 2 to read: Does a player's remaining_potential (overall_rating and potential) trend toward zero as they get older?

The answer to our revised Hypothesis 2 could be useful for team managers. It seems logical that having a general understanding of the age at which most (not all) players reach their potential would help when making personnel choieces. For example, this would be helpful when aquiring players from other teams or as free agents and when deciding bewtween two players of similar skill but at different ages.

Naturally, our first step in answering this question will be to calculate the remaining_potential for each player.

In [29]:
strikers['remaining_potential'] = strikers.potential - strikers.overall_rating    # calc. remaining potential

Conclusions¶

To become an elite striker or passer in the pro football/soccer leagues, players must master a large amount of skills.

Results of Analysis¶

The effect of a strikers (defined as the top 10% of goal scorers) age on their overall rating and remaining potential was investigated. It was found that a strikers age was not a good indicator of the overall rating of a striker (R-sqaured = 0.09), but qualitative results suggest that the best strikers acheive their highest overall rating during the ages of 25 to 35. Striker age was found to be a reasonable indicator of the remaining potential of a striker (R-squared = 0.89). Generally, strikers have reached there maximum potential by age 30.

The professional players who have the most assists (called top passers in this analysis) typically have higher ball control and vision relative to their peers, though as stated earlier, the best players must master a wide skill set and no one attribute solely predicts a player's potential for assists over their career. As always, correlation should not be confused with causation!

Caveats¶

Caveats to this analysis include an incomplete record of match goal and assist data. This missing goal/assist data possibly results in some players appearing to be better than they are relative to their peers (i.e., more of their goals happened to be recorded) or worse relative to thier peers (i.e., less of their goals happened to be recorded). Additionally, the player attributes used in this analysis are from EA Sports FIFA player ratings, the process for the determination of these player attribute values is not known. These attribute values could be called into question, especially if there is some human factor in assigning the values that is not based in actual game play statistics. Further reasearch into how these player attribute values are determined would help in our understanding of the data.

Possible Future Work¶

Future work or improvements based on or related to this analysis could include the evaluation of higher order relationships between player overall_rating and age, which were not well defined by a linear relationship. Also, filtering the goal scorers and players with assists by position might improve the correlation between attributes and goals scored or assists made, since a players position is likely to have some effect on their probability to score or make the final pass before a goal. Comparing the players by exact position might lead to a better apples-to-apples comaprison of goal scorers and passers.
